exercises/practice/circular-buffer/.docs/instructions.md
1:# Instructions
2:
3:A circular buffer, cyclic buffer or ring buffer is a data structure that
4:uses a single, fixed-size buffer as if it were connected end-to-end.
5:
6:A circular buffer first starts empty and of some predefined length. For
7:example, this is a 7-element buffer:
8:
9:<!-- prettier-ignore -->
10:    [ ][ ][ ][ ][ ][ ][ ]
11:
12:Assume that a 1 is written into the middle of the buffer (exact starting
13:location does not matter in a circular buffer):
14:
15:<!-- prettier-ignore -->
16:    [ ][ ][ ][1][ ][ ][ ]
17:
18:Then assume that two more elements are added — 2 & 3 — which get
19:appended after the 1:
20:
21:<!-- prettier-ignore -->
22:    [ ][ ][ ][1][2][3][ ]
23:
24:If two elements are then removed from the buffer, the oldest values
25:inside the buffer are removed. The two elements removed, in this case,
26:are 1 & 2, leaving the buffer with just a 3:
27:
28:<!-- prettier-ignore -->
29:    [ ][ ][ ][ ][ ][3][ ]
30:
31:If the buffer has 7 elements then it is completely full:
32:
33:<!-- prettier-ignore -->
34:    [5][6][7][8][9][3][4]
35:
36:When the buffer is full an error will be raised, alerting the client
37:that further writes are blocked until a slot becomes free.
38:
39:When the buffer is full, the client can opt to overwrite the oldest
40:data with a forced write. In this case, two more elements — A & B —
41:are added and they overwrite the 3 & 4:
42:
43:<!-- prettier-ignore -->
44:    [5][6][7][8][9][A][B]
45:
46:3 & 4 have been replaced by A & B making 5 now the oldest data in the
47:buffer. Finally, if two elements are removed then what would be
48:returned is 5 & 6 yielding the buffer:
49:
50:<!-- prettier-ignore -->
51:    [ ][ ][7][8][9][A][B]
52:
53:Because there is space available, if the client again uses overwrite
54:to store C & D then the space where 5 & 6 were stored previously will
55:be used not the location of 7 & 8. 7 is still the oldest element and
56:the buffer is once again full.
57:
58:<!-- prettier-ignore -->
59:    [C][D][7][8][9][A][B]
60:

